quran[10]{c,v,t}:
  24,11,"Indeed, those who produced the fabrication are a band of you. Do not consider it bad for you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>; rather, it is good for you. For each person of them is whatever sin he has earned, yet the one who played the major role—for him is a great punishment."
  24,12,"If only when you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>heard it, the believing men and the believing women had thought well of themselves{1}and said, “This is an evident fabrication!”",footnotes:1:The Qur’an used the term ‘themselves’ rather than ‘each other’ to make the believerssympathizewith one another by considering any defamation of one as defamation of all.
  24,13,"If only they had produced four witnesses against it. Yet since they did not come up with the witnesses, then before Allah they are the liars."
  24,14,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><i class=""s"">, </i>and His mercy in the Earlier<i class=""s"">(Life) </i>and the Hereafter, you would have been touched by a great punishment for what you have ventured into."
  24,15,"Recall receiving it with your tongues and saying with your mouths what you had no knowledge of, and considering it trivial while with Allah it is greatly serious."
  24,16,"And if only when you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>heard it you had said, “It is not lawful for us to speak about this. Highly Exalted are You; this is a great slander.”"
  24,17,"Allah admonishes you never to return to the like of it if you are believers."
  24,18,"And Allah clarifies the signs to you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>, for Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  24,19,"Indeed, those who love that obscenity should spread among the believers—for them is a painful punishment in the Earlier<i class=""s"">(Life) </i>and the Hereafter, for Allah knows while you know not."
  24,20,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><i class=""s"">, </i>and His mercy, and that Allah is Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy. . .{1}",footnotes:1:According to Al-Alousi and other exegetes, this sentence is left open-ended in order to magnify the predicate and leave it to the reader’s imagination.
